/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

Within this plane, the original "love" that the homosexual love tries to become (but self-sabotages itself and fails, thus getting stuck on lower unresolved levels of confusion and genetic futility) is what can be described as a non-selfless wingman love. Non-selfless - because not actualizing yourself is simply disrespectful towards those who actually wish the best for you. Wingman - because "love", in its basics, is affection of levels where the target of affection is meant to be preserved in some way, and what's a more known preservative of characteristics than making sure the genes (and memes) with desirable characteristics are passed?
It's also interesting to add that homosexuality, just like pansexuality, is a corroder of long-term stable communities.

INTP. Glad to have something to help me procrastinate. I'll do all of them.

>Are you superstitious, or do you believe in supernatural events? What do you think of others who do not share the same belief/disbelief?
Generally no, but I do have an irrational belief in the nature of luck. I will not go into all of it but the general principle of my belief is that luck is a limited but replenishing resource. For example, if something fortunate happens, depending on just how improbable that event was, nothing so good can happen to me again until my pool of luck replenishes. As such, I generally avoid casually relying on chance so as to not accidentally deplete my resources and cause me misfortune when I do something I actually want to succeed at.
>Are you religious?
No, but I do believe in a concept of divinity.
>Are you political?
No. I'm the kind of person that doesn't care until something effects me personally which some would say is a bit scummy but it is what it is and I can't force myself care.
>Have you experienced a significant change in your personality or disposition? Perhaps developed new values or core beliefs? What triggered it?
No. Though some things have changed here and there, I am still the same person at my core that I was a decade ago.
>Which quality of yours do you value/appreciate the most?
My ability to rationally choose the irrational. I may have some bizarre beliefs but you can be sure that I thought out every aspect of it before deciding that is what was best for me. I am glad that I am open minded enough that no option out of the question for me.
>Which quality of yours are you ashamed of the most?
Nothing. My flaws, however deep and alarming some of them may be, contribute to making me the person that I am and I love the person that I am. I would not get rid of a single one.

>>71511417
>Plato-nically and psychologically speaking a perfect form of something is pretty much an archetype of an archetype
Jung/archetypes are neo-Platonic, yea. Platonically the real world is only the imperfect copies of the image, shadows in the cave. Then, the primary project of Platonism and its derivatives is how to turn away from the false copies, how to reconnect with the perfect, the prototypes, the ideal. But to touch on our talk earlier, I think there is a mistake here. The real world is indeed shadows, but so too is the ideal. You leave Plato's cave, only to find another cave beyond, always another in which to hide, with more shadows.

What is eternal is not the ideal, but idealization itself, the longing for ideals. Then, the question is not whether to cling to the real or the ideal, but how you idealize, and how your life reaches for that which it idealizes.

>>71519849
>"I think the [Jungian/MBTI] Theory is meant to be eventually discarded.
I don't think that's quite the correct state of mind. I wouldn't say it should be "discarded", but rather that you should add to it. It's sort of like learning mathematics, you don't discard the teachings you learned from addition once you move on to subtraction or multiplication, etc. But rather you stop focusing on those older concepts, and focus on the new problems which utilize the knowledge you've gained from your studies.
At some point the theory becomes in a sense "useless". You cannot have a purely theoretical knowledge that is also useful. It has to be applied in some manner or form, which makes it no longer purely theoretical. But, if you're entirely focused on the theory you can never actually apply the theory to your own life, which is the purpose of the theory.

Another way to think about it is like learning an instrument. You can study music theory, or the theories behind your specific instrument, but you will never play whatever instrument if you don't put that study to practice. The same concept applies to MBTI (and everything in life).
The purpose of the theory is to be applied to and used in your life in a manner that allows you to easily understand the motives of other people and yourself, with the ultimate goal of understanding yourself so well that you can alter your behaviors in an attempt to make yourself "the ideal person". The thing that should be discarded is the idea that you can only study and somehow improve. It doesn't work like that.

The theory is like the tutorial zone in a new video game. You gotta leave there eventually, because there's nothing more you can gain. At a certain point, only studying the theory had severely diminished returns.

The conclusion there is to make is that both have their own languages they speak in. The first language can't quite effectively convey lots of types of intents the second conveys well, and vice versa.

I wanted to add a few thoughts here, now that I have had some time, as I think it's interesting as it relates to the tension between Jungian theory and MBTI.

The purpose of Jungian typology as I understand is ultimately to be used as a tool for restoring balance within the individual, to reassemble the fragments of their mind.

The purpose of MBTI is to be used as a framework for understanding and negotiating differences as they exist between individuals.

Correct me if I'm wrong, it seems your qualm is that studying personality (past a threshold of diminishing returns) ends up ultimately creating its own confining structure of mind/personality, thus inhibiting the (Jungian) detyping process? And this is why you are ambivalent about participating
Participating is your choice, of course, especially if you feel the threads are bad, you shouldn't torture yourself. I will say though, in defense of MBTI (and its compatibility with the Jungian project), I think it has great potential to facilitate both introspection and understanding between individuals, even if you feel you have transcended its dialectic/conceptual scheme. As such, as I tried to explain somewhat impetuously here >>71522766 (You), I believe it can still serve as a bridge (if not a gateway) in the exploration of other realms of the psyche.

It was 2011. A small town in a rural area of a maligned and overlooked nation.
No one really knew me growing up, but they had elevated and memed me into a shell, an effigy into which it was anything they imagined
So I had enough of a reputation to gather 30-40 people into a modest sized hotel conference hall with a DJ and a large cake, and sandwiches that no one touched.
The first hour was awkward, but as the evening drew in everyone except me eased into enjoyment of the company. I floated between groups and said a few words. I was happy to see them happy but I was isolated.

The DJ took requests but I instructed him to play "Perform This Way" by weird all yankovic instead of "Born This Way" by Lady Gaga, as one of my them was a known Gaga fanatic for some reason.

We were also prohibited from purchasing alcohol, I was the oldest in my year group and the barman became suspicious. So a smuggling operation began where someone who looked over 18 did runs to the local off licence and sneaked them through the railings of the back smoking area, thus guaranteeing intoxication to all.

We also had karaoke, I was cajoled into a performance of "Parklife" by Blur. It is mostly spoken word so a solid choice. I had long hair and was caught in a photo leaping mid chorus, my hair flailing into the air, the crowd flailing wildly with me.

Yeah, it was fun. But I was still broken inside. I'd just landed in a crowd who imagined me to be many things I wasn't, and they found me out by the time we left school the following year and didn't bother with me really since.

Has it really been better since? I don't know. But wanting to make something of myself, to fulfil the few hopes my younger self held in those moments is what keeps me going.

>>71499072
Yes to some extent, 5-meo-mipt and 3-mmc were kind of popular a while back before they got added to the law, and 1p-lsd was a thing until recently, openly sold by twitter accounts importing it from Europe.

The issue is that even if the products you get are technically legal on paper, the cops and the law WILL fuck with you.
For example 1p-LSD is still technically legal, but if I were to order it from NL to JP it would get intercepted at the border, and I would get brought in for questioning about "importing dangerous substances" and stuff like that. Even if they can't really punish me in the end, they will come to my house, maybe question my neighbors and my coworkers, that kind of thing. And it will be written on my record forever.

Some Japs do that kind of thing because they're marginals and don't care about reputational damage, but as a foreigner that has to renew his visa/lease once in a while, this is impossible. If I do this, I will never get another visa or good apartment ever gain. Any lease or job you get has a clause that if you get involved in drugs, they can kick you out right away.

So I only do legal stuff. Which can be enough depending on what drugs you like. Basically you have to like downers.
Nicotine, alcohol, GBL, phenibut, tramadol, codeine, DXM, etc.

I'm more of a stim-empathogen or psych kind of guy so I'm dissatisfied, but I still like alcohol and GBL so it's okay I guess.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>71514100
heres how it goes:
Lasts for 30 seconds but can be quite profound
This is because your red blood cells cant differentiate between nitrous oxide and oxygen so, despite depriving your brain of oxygen, your body doesn't respond - it thinks you're breathing normally.
You wont die or experience nerve damage unless you do a ridiculous amount, usually all at once. Putting one canister into a balloon is standard, but frankly using two in a balloon was always the best. You can stack them, depending on the balloon type, I recall getting six canisters into a balloon before, but dont push it, because while it is fleeting, its a very relieving and therefore behaviorally addictive thing to do. My friends and I used to crush several boxes each on a good night. Also smoke weed first makes it way better.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>71528918
Ecosystem engineers(what you can consider earthworms to be) have actually been linked to at least one mass extinction. The pre-Cambrian period of the Ediacaran is believed to have been transformed into the Cambrian via worms engineering the ecosystem from one of mostly microbial mats to one with churned up soil(thus freeing up nutrients) and altering how things can adhere to surfaces(as microbial mats can make it easier compared to loose sediment, thus limiting a lot of sessile organisms to hard, rocky surfaces which became less abundant). The Ediacaran also saw some of the first signs of large organisms being preyed upon and developing adaptations in the form of mineralizing parts of their bodies. Pic related is a fossil organism from the Ediacaran.

Oh yeah, not really with virology though. In microbiology endosymbionts are pretty abundant and total dependence on their host does occur quite a bit. Yup! Mitochondrion and chloroplasts are also neat in that they've swapped bits of genetic code between them and their hosts. Cyanobacteria also might not have been the first photosynthesizers, there's a pretty good theory out there that the first photosynthesizers actually used a different kind of pigment and were anaerobic(which matches the conditions of early Earth better).
